Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for the organization of the federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments promulgated from 2009 new laws making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon has grown after the November 2010 elections, which have added 675 new Republican representatives to 26 States.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 States were introduced in the year 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity card with photo and proof of American citizenship.
Furthermore, these laws also reduce the periods of advance voting, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of election and withdraw the right to vote from the courts.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present an identity card with a photo.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indian Law.
The Republican authorities endeavoured to extend this practice to other States.
Over the past two years, they sponsored legislation in 34 States to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have universal identity cards such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo identity cards issued by a government agency of their state.
In addition, five million new electors in 2012 do not have such an identity.
However, it often costs over a hundred dollars to obtain the required ID card.
New restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than 35,000 dollars; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required identity card with photos.
Much more.
