In addition, Republican legislators sponsored legislation in 2011 abolishing the registration of voters on polling day in eight States.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voters' registration campaigns contributed to the registration of approximately 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have dropped the registration rate of new electors by 17% in 2010 compared with 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators adopted laws in five other States aimed at reducing the period of advance voting.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, while the voters represented only 13% of the state's voters.
The same was true of the Hispanics.
