According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where it grew the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified.
Jerusalem also houses the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentations, which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 B.C.E.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave small words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the Massada fortress, a former refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 B.C. for his family.
These ruins lie on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering lovers can go there by their own means.
For others, a cable car takes them to this top full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m of altitude, there is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which hosts many tourists during the winter.
A shuttle can drive you from the foot of the mountain.
Ski slopes total 45 km long.
The old beliefs want pagan gods to have inhabited the mountain summit once.
Visit unique museums
This country houses about 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit all of them during one stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth the detour.
First of all: the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
It houses the very ancient manuscripts of Qumran, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Desert of Judaea, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: the Museum of Art of Tel-Aviv.
It mainly includes the canvases of impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of wettings of visitors and overseers of the time.
Once in Césarée, enter the only Private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are forbidden.
The fifth museum is the Museum of the Holocaust or Memorial of Yad Vashem, located in Tel-Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages of history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and enter into total darkness.
Stars sparkle.
You then hear the names of Jewish children and the names of countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
The three large seaside resorts of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can bathe in the Red Sea even in winter, because the water temperature does not fall below 21° while the air temperature can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even hotter and you can bathe there all year round.
By the way, it is the world's most unique sea: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, or 417 m below sea level.
The blue water contains brine and very easily holds the bathers, even those who cannot swim.
The landscapes surrounding it are of surrealistic beauty.
There we come to perform a treatment based on salt water, lemon, curative sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, but also to simply relax.
