Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the Agency, it was the second Member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had undertaken close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, the road from Poland to outer space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always encounter understanding.
For example, I would like to refer to A. Šternfeld's conference at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, in which he presented ideas drawn from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astroutics ".
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the cold listeners and later years Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld obtained in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch award for his work "Introduction to Astroutics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a propagator of world-renowned astronomicals, and his contribution has been rewarded in particular by the fact that his name has been given to one of the craters of the moon's hidden face.
As early as 1925, a dam was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
Nor is it clear whether the rocket should be used to propel or to brake the drain.
The only known information on this root is that of the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to the rockets.
The research was conducted by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the preserved documents that this research has reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, research has ceased.
In 1937, the plans of a photographic hunting rocket, designed by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" was published by a writer named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects had a military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were conducted by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Doradczo-Naukowy Committee"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to Polish astronomical society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is a question of a company in the November 1954 issue of the Journal Problem, in which there are four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Subotowicze, it is proposed to create an astronomical company
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish astronomical company (PTA) made efforts to enter the international astronomical federation (created in 1951) and as early as the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the international astronomical federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 metres was 80 cm long and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of RM-1A was built, and during the summer of 1959, flight tests of two-storey RM-2 were started in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 metres long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and serve to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963 all the development work was halted.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded in the first MRI-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all such equipment was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Later on, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
The entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national committee COSPAR two years later.
