The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on public utility work.
This decision raised a serious discussion in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Liberal-oriented economic systems, both in the EU and in the context of globalization, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This actually means that the different economic entities and national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of freedom of trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital combined with financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour prices (wages) generate price tension.
The following meaning must be put to an end: a producer is trying to import goods sold at low prices to resist economic competition by "making the price of the competitor more expensive" in order to remove a greater share of the market and thus increase its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either to transfer production abroad, to buy at low prices, or to disappear. The result is a major unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Given that private capital has no social responsibility and hence responsibility for the unemployment generated by the private capital, the state's social burdens are necessarily increasing.
All of this reinforces the perfect unwillingness of the entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for the benefit of the company.
This situation is at such a public level that there is no need to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which governments in different countries are forced to engage in a mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own people in order to attract foreign capital to their homes.
In other words, governments place their own people at the expense of private capital without regard for social collapse.
This appears primarily in the amendments to the laws in force.
The objective is to compel its own people to accept the private capital price diktat, particularly in the area of wages.
This occurs on the one hand by a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and by the restriction of employees' rights in the field of labour law.
As a result, there is increasing poverty and deepening differences between the rich and the poor.
In RFA, there have been public food distribution points for the poor for years that cannot meet their needs with their own work.
The number of these people is already estimated at millions of times.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it becomes quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is obliged to pay an extra fee so that they can achieve the minimum life.
This scandal, for example, has been updated in the case of employees working as assistants to the federal parliament.
The economic measures of almost all the Member States of the south of the EU undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century), or to live with poor wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital will invest in their country.
Here is the question: where does that capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or then a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to all Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media claim, at the same time, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital strongly supports the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
The question is, then, whether private capital does not influence and, even today, does not govern, according to its own selfish interests, politics and by the same, the whole state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The evidence is that there is an almost all-powerful lobby present in all States.
As a result, a desperate situation arises in the area of corruption, by granting mutual benefits, in the legislation, where everything is punishable but not punishable.
In RFA, the situation is such that due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the development of draft laws to law firms closely related to industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
The whole power comes not from the people, as the Western constitutions state, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is evident that liberal-oriented democracies are now faced with the situation described by Appianos in his book "the crisis of the Roman Empire in the time of Caesar and Pompeii": "The state was long in delicence and the functions were attributed by violence.
The coups de pot-de-vine, the favors obtained illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The underground and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with voices already sold" ... ... "The honest people did not seek to obtain any functions, it resulted in once the state remained 8 months without consulates".... 'We really began to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was an autocratism and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man"... It is true that Appianos had in mind Pompée, but it is Caesar who irreversibly transformed democracy into an absoluteist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on preference for personal profit, without regard for the interests of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and promote the interests of society as a whole.
Today, as in the past, this results in an unprecedented decline in elites, without any effort to carry out far-reaching reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the present state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems can be seen as a kind of break before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites completely ignore the eventuality of hundreds of thousands of future loss in human lives, the humanitarian and social crises that we are now witnessing and the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and internally, the Government of the Czech Republic will continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution is socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investments in the economy, increase citizens' influence on government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
