The film Argo: when everything goes to hell, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters made up of Islamic students attacked the American Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats in hostages.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had supported his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the U.S. government a positive outcome, but it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow for the prestige of the United States, further aggravated by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The diplomats who were kidnapped were finally released 444 days later, following the negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate evokes a wave of solidarity and an anti-iranian feeling in the United States.
The Iranian debacle greatly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat in front of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by the actor and screenwriter Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory in America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated events, they found themselves in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with a rocambole cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team who came to make screenings for the shooting of a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan of the exfiltration expert Tony Mendez demands Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, with the film based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is on the one hand a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful blow, a betrayal - for example, in the Ocean's Leven trilogy, twelve and thirteen.
The ambiances follow: sequences of Tehran in documentary style (in the sub-titled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and the way in which, through these photos, these same situations have been retransscribed in the film, there are no great differences),
the lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with dressed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his game of actor ceased to raise ironic remarks.
Argo is his third film after the police shadow " Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The City" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film that does not take place in his home city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where Tehran's role is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity, which also suggests the confusion and unpredictableness that occurs when, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the false shooting team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions at too many locations
The director had to be content with a subject offering only a few exciting scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It goes well, it sometimes adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at the Tehran airport is separated by a phone call in America and the continuation on the landing track is quite drawn by the hair).
The weakness of Argo lies in its dissipated nature, due to the need to show too many events to too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-opers, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from there, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks some dramatic tension, it is seen with moderate interest, appreciating the achievements and retro style of the 1970s.
It leads the viewer, but with difficulty.
