Here's my proposal for the Spijkenisse mountain of books, or as we say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million-euro mountain has ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project including an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and some buildings and mitoyenne houses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus this little burgade terne, which so far had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of a harsh lacidour, whose white facades invite to think that they are home to a dairy, has enriched themselves with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
True, an elevator carries you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open to you when you crowd the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the soil in Dutch bricks and the elegant reverbs speak unequivocally the language of municipal public places.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public banks, dogs and small boys and girls playing at the ball.
And everywhere books, books and even books.
"The library's rays are usually located along the facade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," Willy Maas explains.
We have completely upset the classical spatial configuration and opened up the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been properly adapted: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the centre for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A special beauty lies in the library's black rays, which are sometimes of the lamps, sometimes of the balustrades, sometimes of the staircase ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," said Joop Trouborst, project leader at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in an agricultural company.
In the Netherlands, the synthetic membrane of a millimetre thick has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and time-consuming.
The final membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 metres, the literary coffee offers a breathtaking view of the city, as well as Dutch croquettes and ficus pots.
They create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to the maintenance of the ideal level of moisture in the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project on ecology," Trouborst says.
The temperature of the building is adjusted by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun illuminates only little time inside, even the days of good weather.
The thick beams of wood mounted across the glass facade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned septic computer scientist, has already been at risk of entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, describes even Boekenberg as "the finally found soul" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure has helped to fill the library's gaps that were not yet fully garnished (today, it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays overflow everywhere.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has reached the master discipline called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new history page.
Even if she may appear young and uneducated.
Finally, this is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose to abstain when voting on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian demand for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence without, however, being too critical of Israel.
During the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose to abstain when voting on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have any difficulty in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy, so to speak, defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are therefore facing several fronts.
We expect them to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find this role, but they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
External policy, such as in France or Great Britain
What, then, does the term "normal" foreign policy really mean for Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national dossiers.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Near East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of the other great powers: that is why Germany has to protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position of Germany with regard to the conflict in the Near East and the abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany has first important opportunities in the Near East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to undermine public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive element.
However, I would not give too much importance to this because it is not purely unilateral.
But this is in any case a key element in German strategic reflections.
Does Germany harm its relations with the United States by choosing abstention during major votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will only be respected.
Germany has thus shown that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, views on the Palestinian initiative vary.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do the views differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration secretly shows great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem.
If you observe the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from overwhelmed with enthusiasm about Netanyahou's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other hand?
I don't think it's easy for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot therefore enter a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing in the euro issue.
In my opinion, Germany will take a locomotive role in the future and push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been sensitive.
But in my view, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that further marks their independence.
Does Germany see itself playing a major role on the international stage, and does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or is it still difficult to assume leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable to it and, for obvious reasons, the country still faces difficulties in playing a more important role.
Looking, for example, at the euro crisis, it is noted that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed of neighbors and very varied opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the United States' influence on European policy only diminishes, but at the moment, the EU does not fill this gap, so who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're only less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy of Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
