The Unasur summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The VIth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) today ended in Peru without the release of the Lima Declaration, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven representatives present.
Ephe tried several times to access the document signed at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially indicated that it would be disclosed after the summit was closed, and then stated that it would be published at one time on the Peruvian government's website at another.
When questioned on the text, they reported that its content had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief press statements.
The access of journalists to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The limited information circulated among journalists was that given by the press officers of some of the Unasur governments that attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, Peru's presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the speech of President Humala and not of the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru was host to the Third Summit of South America (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although this was requested by the press, it had also not circulated the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the ASPA official site, it can be verified that the document was published in March last year.
In both international meetings, Peruvian authorities have tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that splits a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and declared that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the supporters of both parties in the trial that Lima had attempted against Santiago and that began on Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are bringing before this international court today," said President Humala, next to his Chilean counterpart.
