Hector "Hetin" Reyes "The basketball is my whole life"
The basketball balloon "Hetin" Reyes spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the land and, thanks to him, traveled all over the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as large as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage condemns him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether it is as a lower league player, player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, the NSB, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I wore several jackets in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the NSB, director general of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," recalls Reyes during a visit of Primera Hora to Bayamón, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for over 50 years.
Basketball is my whole life.
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that recall his route without standards, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, those he loves most are those who remind him of his passage as a player in the Vaqueros team in the middle of the 1950s until 1982, after having spent 15 years as co-manager or team manager.
"This was my best years, the ones I've enjoyed most because I've had the chance to participate in eight Vacheros championships since 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
This has been a great deal of satisfaction for many years, including the five championships between 1971 and 1975.
I then retired at the 1981 championship, the year Jerome Mincy joined the NSB team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead from the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been in charge here and who was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me: "I have a hard player for you, it measures two meters.
