That's how Mincy, one of Puerto Rico's best players started.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse was going to help us try to win another.
He was pleased with the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manate of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of Mincy's and his duties on the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States during the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then, there was the 1990 World Cup, where we got to the 4th and we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge hadn't let us play the last game, said Reyes.
Is the 1990 World Team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite is that of the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won the gold and we cut the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that won the bronze during the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 because of a problem of knees.
