A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
This semester, when Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible trap: the end of the "great score" of the Mayan calendar, on December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the impending world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea of what awaited him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax chauffeur that some called the "Armageddon of Debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theologians of the end of time thought the apocalypse would be triggered.
"I didn't realize that this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Professor Charmé said this week to his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey).
If we look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we reported it, it was a very good time.
And you must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to teach about "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last of history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human behavior.
If the nuclear weapon fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could explode.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the University of State of Pennsylvania, the History Professor of Latin America Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an Assistant Professor of History of Art and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply called "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world would not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "neighbourishing disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the State of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night of the end of the supposed world," said Restall.
Courses have become quite popular.
"It was completed in two hours," Restall said about his course for high-level students, composed of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort each other," says Briggid Robinson, a 23-year-old sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, Rutgers-Camden University.
